Growth rates were determined by nonlinear regression (KaleidaGraph, Synergy Software; and Microsoft Excel) using a modified version of the Gompertz equation [Eq. (1)] (Begot et al., 1996). Regression parameters included the time of measurement (t), growth rate (k), lag time (L), and the maximum \documentclass{aastex}\usepackage{amsbsy}\usepackage{amsfonts}\usepackage{amssymb}\usepackage{bm}\usepackage{mathrsfs}\usepackage{pifont}\usepackage{stmaryrd}\usepackage{textcomp}\usepackage{portland, xspace}\usepackage{amsmath, amsxtra}\usepackage{upgreek}\pagestyle{empty}\DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}\begin{document}
$$\log \left( { { \frac { \Delta OD }  { \Delta O { D_ { { \rm { min } } } } } } } \right)$$
\end{document} value (A). For the regressions, the final OD values for the inoculum-negative controls were negligible, thereby indicating no measurable contamination or formation of nonbiological particulate matter after cultivation.
